ce:section.ce:para:
Time-resolved PL measurements were performed with a resolution of about 0.4–0.6 ns to gain insights on the PL mechanism (see Fig. 7
                     ). The decay time curves were best fitted by two exponential decays, as typically reported in the literature [2,14,45], and the resulting decay times are summarized in Table 2
                      (decays of silica blue emission agree with previously reported data [46] (Fig. SI-7)). The time profiles are clearly non linear in the semi-log plots, suggesting a multiexponential decay model, as frequently reported in the literature. From the model we can extract the mean lifetime and the fractional contributions of each component (see details on the multiexponential decay model in the Supplementary Information) [47]. The two exctracted decays are in the 0.5–1.2 ns and 4–6 ns range. The first one is within the experimental time resolution (0.4–0.6 ns as shown by the full width at half-maximum, fwhm, of the laser signal reported in Fig. 7) and its discussion is therefore outside the chances of the present experiment. However, we have also observed that this decay affects the emission spectrum as a whole, suggesting the presence of a non-radiative contribution that can be accessed from the entire chromophore ensemble related to the recorded emission.
